  <span id="freeText12793563799278842272" style="display:none">This was pretty good most of the way through, though I think it may have been just a hair too long, since by the end I found myself wondering what it added to have the timelines and characters all mixed up, where at the start I found this pleasing. <br /><br />As a side note, this book makes me wonder if those who claim great originality for the likes of Pynchon and DFWallace for doing exactly this kind of mixing up are either underread or full of it. I am not even sure that this technique was invented in the modern or postmodern periods, however much it has come to be associated with them. </span>
