<div id="review_2828089923" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2828089923" />
    <a title="Jerry" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/21430140-jerry"><img alt="Jerry" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1566521416p2/21430140.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2828089923?book_show_action=true">May 25, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Jerry" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Jerry" href="/user/show/21430140-jerry">Jerry</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Hardcover 9780394539959" href="/book/show/1775541.Solomon_Gursky_Was_Here">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2828089923" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer10905639688847741385"><blockquote><br/>	There was, they said, ice lodged in Mr. Bernard’s heart, glacial ice, but he had come by it honestly.<br/></blockquote><br/><br/>Moses Berger is the failed son of a famous, in the right circles, poet; this may be why he obsesses over the history of the Gursky family with its many failed sons. The book jumps back and forth between people and ages; from Ephraim Gursky, who came from London to the great white north, through his three grandsons (his son Aaron gets very little attention) and great grandsons and granddaughters.</span>
  <span id="freeText10905639688847741385" style="display:none"><blockquote><br />	There was, they said, ice lodged in Mr. Bernard’s heart, glacial ice, but he had come by it honestly.<br /></blockquote><br /><br />Moses Berger is the failed son of a famous, in the right circles, poet; this may be why he obsesses over the history of the Gursky family with its many failed sons. The book jumps back and forth between people and ages; from Ephraim Gursky, who came from London to the great white north, through his three grandsons (his son Aaron gets very little attention) and great grandsons and granddaughters. It jumps from the 1800s (at least 1851) and into the eighties (at least 1983). The paranoids in the book (and there is a lot of paranoia, some overt, some subtle) go from a fear of a new ice age to a fear of frying.<br /><br />It jumps from Washington DC to the Polar Sea and, in some asides, far south.<br /><br />It is told mostly in the order in which Moses discovers a topic, which makes it nearly impossible to follow; there is a family tree in the front to help orient the reader. It lacks years, because the reader needs to be disoriented. Everybody else is.<br /><br />Most of the attention goes to Moses, who is financially and sexually tied up with the Gurskys; and Solomon Gursky, who learned wilderness skills, and potentially quite a few other skills, from Ephraim, and who is, literally, everywhere.<br /><br />It is filled with the stories of unreliable narrators as told by unreliable narrators. Some of the stories seem nearly supernatural, drawing from both “Eskimaux” and Jewish traditions.<br /><br />The generations repeat the mistakes of their ancestors, making later stories seem weirdly familiar. They also repeat rituals, deliberately and perhaps accidentally, in keeping with the uncertain supernatural elements.<br /><br />I was inspired to read this book by a combination of (1) preparing for a Montreal visit last year, and, when looking for dead authors to stalk, discovering the name Mordecai Richler, and (2) reading Mark Steyn’s essay on Richler in <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/200168.From_Head_to_Toe_An_Anatomical_Anthology" title="From Head to Toe An Anatomical Anthology by Mark Steyn" rel="nofollow noopener">From Head to Toe</a>.</span>
  <a data-text-id="10905639688847741385" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

